{
  "texts": [
    "In this case, the stream includes a deactivation event at time 𝑡 𝑖 for the temperature being in the range 15-18°C, and an activation event at time 𝑡 𝑖+1 for the temperature being in the range 19-24°C.We convert the stream of events into a stream of sensor states, where a sensor state 𝑠𝑡 (𝜎𝑖, 𝑡 𝑠, 𝑡 𝑒) denotes that the sensor state 𝜎 𝑖 (derived from 𝑆 𝑖) is true during the time interval [𝑡 𝑠, 𝑡 𝑒].",
    "For instance, 𝑠𝑡 (FridgeDoorOpen, 12:32pm, 12:33pm) represents the fact that the fridge door was open in the interval [12:32pm, 12:33pm].",
    "As another example, the 𝑠𝑡 (NearTheStove, 11:45am, 12:00pm) represent the fact that the motion sensor near the stove detected the subject's movements from 11:45am to 12:00pm.",
    "More formally, we generate a sensor state 𝑠𝑡 (𝜎, 𝑡 𝑠, 𝑡 𝑒) when the stream contains two events 𝐸 𝑆 𝑡 𝑠 and 𝐸 𝑆 𝑡 𝑒 with 𝑡 𝑠 < 𝑡 𝑒 being the instants in which the events of activation and de-activation of sensor 𝑆 occurred, 𝜎 indicates a property revealed by the activation state of 𝑆, and there is no 𝐸 𝑆 𝑡 𝑞 such that 𝑡 𝑠 < 𝑡 𝑞 < 𝑡 𝑒. 3.3.2 Segmentation.",
    "ADL-LLM employs a fixed-time segmentation of the stream of sensor states, considering windows of 𝜏 seconds and an overlap factor 𝑜."
  ]
}